We will fit a penalized spline on the temperature-heat consumption relationship.

Define a function that fits the spline given the target data y, the basis matrix B, the degrees of freedom df and the smoothing/regularization parameter $\lambda$.

In [169]:
def spline_fit(y, B, df, lambda_=1.0):
    # build difference matrix
    P = np.diff(np.diag(np.ones(df)), n=1, axis=1)
    D = np.dot(P, P.T)
    # build the augmented matrices
    if(y.ndim ==1):
        y_ = np.vstack((np.expand_dims(y, axis=1), np.zeros((df, 1))))
    
    else:
        y_ = np.vstack((y, np.zeros((df, 1))))
    X_ = np.vstack((B, np.sqrt(lambda_) * D))
    
    return sm.OLS(y_, X_).fit()

Next, we define the generalized cross-validation score to choose the optimal value of $\lambda$. The GCV score is given by

$\operatorname{GCV}(\lambda) = \frac{n \sum_{i = 1}^n \left(y_i - \hat{y}_i\right)^2}{\left(n - \operatorname{tr} \mathbf{H}\right)^2}.$

Here, $\hat{y}_i$ is the $i$-th predicted value, and $\mathbf{H}$ is upper left $n \times n$ submatrix of the the influence matrix for the OLS model $\mathbf{\tilde{y}} = \mathbf{\tilde{X}} + \varepsilon$.

In [170]:
def gcv_score(results, df):
    X = results.model.exog[:-df, :]
    n = X.shape[0]
    y = results.model.endog[:n]
    
    y_hat = results.predict(X)
    hat_matrix_trace = results.get_influence().hat_matrix_diag[:n].sum()
    
    return n * np.power(y - y_hat, 2).sum() / np.power(n - hat_matrix_trace, 2)

Finally, we define a function to combine spline fitting and cross-validation.

In [171]:
def qspline(y, x, df, hasconst=True):
    
    if hasconst:
        basis_matrix = patsy.dmatrix('1 + bs(x, df)', {"x": x, "df": df})
        df += 1
    else:
        basis_matrix = patsy.dmatrix('bs(x, df) - 1', {"x": x, "df": df})
    
    lambdas = np.logspace(0, 50, 100, base=1.5) * 1e-8
    gcv_scores = np.array([gcv_score(spline_fit(y, basis_matrix, df, lambda_=lambda_), df) for lambda_ in lambdas])
    lambda_best = lambdas[gcv_scores.argmin()]
    results = spline_fit(y, basis_matrix, df, lambda_=lambda_best)
    return results, basis_matrix

Since this pattern is after we have accounted for ambient temperature variation, we can hypothesize that it is caused by a residents starting their vaciations as summer approaches (a "time of year" effect).

We can fit a second spline that captures this yearly cycle, through a backfitting procedure.

In [178]:
def backfit():

    rsquared = 0 
    spline_time = 0
    spline_temperature = 0
    t = range(len(heat))

    for _ in range(100):

        resid = heat - spline_time
        results, basis_matrix = qspline(resid, temperature, 4)
        spline_temperature = results.predict(patsy.build_design_matrices([basis_matrix.design_info], 
                                                                                      {'x': temperature})[0])

        if(abs(results.rsquared - rsquared) < 0.0001):
            print('Loop finished because R-squared stopped improving')
            break
        else:
            rsquared = results.rsquared
            resid = heat - spline_temperature
            results, basis_matrix = qspline(resid, t, 4, hasconst=False)
            spline_time = results.predict(patsy.build_design_matrices([basis_matrix.design_info], {'x': t})[0])
            
    return spline_temperature, spline_time, results

A first observation is that even when accounting for temperature and time-of-year effects, heat consumption is characterized by significantly higher variance than electrcity consumption. This means that focusing on heat consumption practices may lead us to discover greater energy saving opportunities.

When interpreting the plot above, one must keep in mind that any succesful model is able to explain away some of the variance in the data. While heat consumption is depicted after applying the model for temperature and time-of-year effects, the electricity consumption is depicted as is, i.e. before any part of its variance is eliminated using day-of-week or time-of-year variables.

A second observation is that the residuals exhibit positive autocorrelation:

In [227]:
'It is ' + '{0:.2f}'.format(durbin_watson(resid)) + ', when 0 corresponds to perfect positive correlation'

It is 0.57, when 0 corresponds to perfect positive correlation

This means that we cannot use the confidence intervals from the regression model. We could whiten the data by removing the estimated autocorrelation: $(2 - durbin\_watson\_statistic) /2$. However, since temperature and time-of-year are also autocorrelated, both temperature and time-of-year will be overshadowed by the predictive power of the lagged variable.

Instead, we will focus on achieving the following:

1. Reducing the variance of the heat consumption. Succesful rules on more efficient use of heating/cooling equipment should be able to reduce the (local) variance of heat consumption under similar conditions of ambient air temperature and time of year. When examined locally (i.e., during a short time window), people living in the pilot building have a very regular occupancy pattern; this supports the argument of judging the performace of the derived rules by their ability to lower variation.

2. Challenging setpoint preferences/habits. Affecting setpoint preferences means affecting the curve that represents the average contribution of ambient air temperature to heat consumption. After the end of the pilot, we can follow the same approach as the one presented here, so as to derive the new curve, and assess the corresponding energy savings by applying the same temperature time-series on both spline models.
